<exercises xml:id="ex-MoreDefiniteIntegrals">
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Explain how we can use the different types of symmetry can help us as we evaluate the definite integral <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=-a}^{x=a} f(x)\;dx</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the definition of <em>even symmetric</em> (where <m>f(-x) = f(x)</m> for all <m>x</m>-values) to explain why <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=-4}^{x=4} f(x)\;dx = 2\displaystyle\int_{x=0}^{x=4}f(x)\;dx</m> for an even symmetric function <m>f(x)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the definition of <em>odd symmetric</em> (where <m>f(-x) = -f(x)</m> for all <m>x</m>-values) to explain why <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=-4}^{x=4} f(x)\;dx = 0</m> for an odd symmetric function <m>f(x)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Assume that <m>f(x)</m> is some even symmetric function with <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=0}^{x=6} f(x)\;dx = 4</m> and <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=-3}^{x=0} f(x) \;dx= 9</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Sketch a possible graph of the function <m>f(x)</m>, and shade in the areas from the integrals listed.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=0}^{x=3} f(x)\;dx</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=3}^{x=6} f(x)\;dx</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=-6}^{x=-3} f(x)\;dx</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=-6}^{x=6} f(x)\;dx</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Assume that <m>g(x)</m> is some odd symmetric function with <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=0}^{x=6} g(x)\;dx = 4</m> and <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=-3}^{x=0} g(x) \;dx= 9</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Sketch a possible graph of the function <m>g(x)</m>, and shade in the areas from the integrals listed.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=0}^{x=3} g(x)\;dx</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=3}^{x=6} g(x)\;dx</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=-6}^{x=-3} g(x)\;dx</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=-6}^{x=6} g(x)\;dx</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Explain how to find the average height of a function on an interval. Why does this work?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Note that <m>y=\sin(x)</m> is odd symmetric and <m>y=x^2</m> is even symmetric.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Show that <m>f(x) = x^2\sin(x)</m> is odd symmetric by showing that <m>f(-x) = -f(x)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=-\pi}^{x=\pi} x^2\sin(x)\;dx</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p>
                    You shouldn't need to find an antiderivative for this function, which is good news (since this is a tricky function to antidifferentiate).
                </p>
            </hint>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the average height of <m>f(x)</m> on the interval <m>[-\pi, \pi]</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Note that <m>y=\cos(x)</m> is even symmetric and <m>y=x^2</m> is even symmetric.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Show that <m>f(x) = x^2\cos(x)</m> is even symmetric by showing that <m>f(-x) = f(x)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Given that <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=0}^{x=\pi} x^2\cos(x)\;dx = -2\pi</m>, evaluate <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=-\pi}^{x=\pi} x^2\cos(x)\;dx</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the average height of <m>f(x)</m> on the interval <m>[-\pi,\pi]</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Find the average height of the following functions on the intervals listed.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(x) = e^x -x</m> on <m>[0,3]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>g(x) = \cos(x) + x</m> on <m>\left[0,\frac{\pi}{2}\right]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>j(x) = \dfrac{1}{1+x^2}</m> on <m>[-1,1]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\ell(x) = \dfrac{1}{x^2}</m> on <m>[1,4]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
</exercises>